# Swift Student Challenge 2026 - Submission Form Responses

Copy-paste each section into its corresponding field.

---

## What problem is your app playground trying to solve and what inspired you to solve it?
*(200 words max)*

In 2018, Kerala flooded. It was the worst in a century. The Malayalam film 2018 later showed the world what that looked like, but I didn't need a film. I was fourteen, in Chennai, calling home to Thalassery while my mother tried reaching relatives across Kannur. Calls kept dropping. People we knew were stranded for days with no power and no signal. Nobody could look up whether the water was still rising or what to do if someone got hurt.

Then in 2024, the Wayanad landslides hit one district away from my hometown. Chooralmala, Mundakkai. Places people in Kannur drive to for weekends. Gone overnight. Rescuers dug through mud with bare hands. Again, people had phones, and the phones had nothing useful on them.

We Keralites show up for each other. Neighbours become rescue teams. Fishermen become first responders. But showing up isn't enough when you don't know what to do.

Revive is a fully offline survival guide. 556 techniques, 15 emergency triage trees, 2,048 step-by-step instructions. No server calls, no internet needed. It puts first-responder-level knowledge on a device people already carry.

---

## Who would benefit from your app playground and how?
*(200 words max)*

Anyone who spends time in areas with unreliable connectivity. Hikers, campers, rural communities, disaster-affected families, travellers in remote regions. In India alone, the Western Ghats, the Himalayas, and the Northeast see hundreds of emergencies every year where people have smartphones but no signal.

The first group is people facing an active emergency. The triage system asks branching questions like a first responder would and narrows 556 techniques to the right one in three taps. A parent whose child is choking doesn't need to know the Heimlich manoeuvre exists. They tap "I'm Hurt," answer two questions, and the app tells them what to do.

Second, people who want to be prepared. The guide covers 10 domains from fire-starting to shelter construction for anyone planning backcountry travel.

Third, communities in disaster-prone regions. Kerala floods, Wayanad landslides, the 2015 Chennai floods that submerged the city I grew up in. These events cut connectivity for days. An offline app with medically accurate first aid, emergency signalling tools like the SOS flashlight and siren, and a built-in compass becomes genuinely useful on a device everyone already owns.

No account needed. No internet needed. Works instantly.

---

## How did accessibility factor into your design process?
*(200 words max)*

It was a core constraint from the start because the app's main use case involves bad conditions. Someone using Revive might be injured, in the dark, panicking, or unable to use their hands. That shaped every decision.

I built hands-free voice control using SFSpeechRecognizer and AVSpeechSynthesizer. Users can navigate step-by-step guides entirely by voice. Commands like "next step," "repeat," and "go back" work without touching the screen. The app reads instructions aloud, which matters when your hands are applying pressure to a wound or holding a splint.

All SF Symbol images have VoiceOver annotations. Decorative icons use accessibilityHidden(true), and interactive elements have descriptive accessibilityLabel values. The triage flow uses large tap targets (minimum 56pt) and high-contrast text on dark backgrounds.

The app is dark-mode only. Not for looks. It preserves night vision and reduces battery drain when charging isn't an option.

Typography supports Dynamic Type. Emergency screens use bold, high-contrast layouts that stay readable under stress. Onboarding includes a skip option so users can reach critical content right away.

Siri integration through AppIntents lets users trigger the emergency siren or search techniques completely hands-free.

Every design choice assumes the user is not comfortable.

---

## Did you use open source software, other than Swift?

**No.** The app uses only first-party Apple frameworks: SwiftUI, SwiftData, AVFoundation, CoreLocation, CoreMotion, Speech (SFSpeechRecognizer), AVSpeechSynthesizer, and AppIntents. No third-party packages, no SPM dependencies.

---

## Did you use any content that you don't have ownership rights to?

**Yes.** Medical protocols and first aid procedures are based on published guidelines from the American Heart Association, World Health Organization, and wilderness medicine textbooks. All content was rewritten in my own words for step-by-step instructional use. No text was copied verbatim. SF Symbols used throughout the app are provided by Apple.

---

## Did you use AI tools?

**Yes.**

I used Claude and Gemini throughout development. Specifically for scaffolding SwiftUI views and boilerplate, debugging compilation and layout issues, cross-referencing medical protocols across multiple sources like AHA and WHO guidelines, generating and validating structured JSON data, and auditing SF Symbol icon names for correctness.

All architectural decisions, triage tree branching logic, UI/UX design, content accuracy verification, and emergency protocol sequencing were done by me. I understand the full codebase including the AVAudioSourceNode waveform synthesis, the SFSpeechRecognizer voice command pipeline, and every triage branch in ContentDatabase.swift. AI tools made implementation faster but they did not decide what a panicking user should see first, how triage branches should resolve, or which medical sources to trust. The core idea, that the app should think like a first responder and not like a search engine, is mine.

---

## What other technologies did you use in your app playground, and why did you choose them?
*(200 words max)*

SwiftUI for the entire interface. Chosen for composability and built-in dark mode support.

SwiftData for user-generated content like saved waypoints, kit items, favourites, and history. Picked it over Core Data for the simpler Swift-native API.

SFSpeechRecognizer and AVSpeechSynthesizer for hands-free voice control. Users navigate guides by voice and hear instructions read aloud. Works completely on-device.

CoreLocation for the offline compass, coordinate display, and waypoint tracking. All location data stays on the device.

AVFoundation for the SOS flashlight using the torch API for Morse code signalling, and for the emergency siren, which generates a real-time frequency-sweeping waveform through AVAudioSourceNode.

AppIntents for Siri Shortcuts integration. Users can trigger the siren or search techniques through Siri without opening the app.

CoreMotion for the inclinometer tool that measures slope angles for shelter site selection and avalanche risk assessment.

Every technology was chosen because it works offline. Nothing in the app requires a network connection.

